column11: This question was closed with the correct answer 'Catherine Cortez Masto (D)' with an end date of 8 November 2016. Catherine Cortez Masto was elected senator in Nevada on November 8. (NY Times) See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated

Clinton is likely to win Nevada based on Democrats' favored status there in 2012 and 2008, and given the likely rise in the Hispanic vote. Therefore with a presidential election turnout and given the prominence of Harry Reid and his retirement, enough Democrats will also turn out to elect Masto as the next U.S. Senator.

Hispanic and Democratic Get Out the Vote ground game is stronger. Marijuana legalization is on the ballot which will drive the younger people to the polls. Trump continues to demonize everything Hispanic/Latino. This fuels this backlash.

The polling average over the last two months has Heck up about 2-4%. Polls have been off by quite a bit in the past mostly due to the difficulty in polling and predicting turnout for the large hispanic population there. I wouldn't be surprised to see the Democrats (both Clinton and Cortez Masto) outperform again this year. That said, it's also a bad idea to completely ignore the polls there, and they've been pretty consistent for Heck, so I'll give him the edge at this point.

Though still classified as a toss up, Nevada looks to be slipping out of the Democrats' hands. There's not much of an incumbency factor with Harry Reid stepping down, and Joe Heck seems a strong candidate, unlike Sharron Angle who lost to him in the primary.
